@node Overview
@chapter Overview

@samp{anki-noter.el} uses a large language model (via @samp{gptel}) to generate Anki flashcards from various source materials and inserts them as org-mode headings formatted for @samp{anki-editor}.  It bridges two workflows: reading source material and producing spaced-repetition cards, by delegating the extraction of atomic knowledge to an LLM@. @*

The package accepts three kinds of input: @*

@itemize
@item
The current buffer or active region. @*
@item
An external file, including PDFs (with native multimodal support for Anthropic and Google backends, and a @samp{pdftotext} fallback for others). @*
@item
A URL, whose content is fetched and rendered before being sent to the LLM@. @*
@end itemize

Generated cards are inserted as org-mode subtrees at point, with the correct heading level and property drawers (@code{ANKI_DECK}, @code{ANKI_NOTE_TYPE}, @code{ANKI_TAGS}, @code{ANKI_FORMAT}) already in place.  After insertion, the package optionally pushes the new notes to Anki via @samp{anki-editor}. @*

A template system lets users switch between prompt strategies for different domains---general non-fiction, language learning, programming---and custom templates can be added through the @code{anki-noter-prompt-templates} user option (@ref{Template configuration}). @*

The single entry point is the @samp{M-x anki-noter} command, which opens a transient menu where you configure the source, target, and generation options before invoking the generate action (@ref{The transient menu}). @*

The package requires Emacs 28.1 or later, @samp{gptel} 0.9+, and @samp{anki-editor} 0.3+.  The @samp{transient} library is also required, but it is bundled with Emacs 28.1 and later. @*

