@node Card generation
@section Card generation

@vindex anki-noter-card-count
@vindex anki-noter-language
@vindex anki-noter-anki-format

The user option @code{anki-noter-card-count} sets the default target number of cards to generate.  It accepts either an integer or @code{nil}.  When @code{nil} (the default), the LLM decides how many cards are appropriate for the given source material.  Set this to a specific number when you want consistent output size---for instance, when processing many short passages and you want roughly five cards from each.  This default can be overridden per invocation via the @samp{c} key in the transient menu (@ref{The transient menu}). @*

The user option @code{anki-noter-language} controls the output language for generated cards.  When @code{nil} (the default), cards are generated in the same language as the source material.  Set this to a language name (e.g., @samp{"Spanish"}) to produce cards in a different language---useful, for example, when reading English-language material but studying in your native language.  This default can be overridden per invocation via the @samp{l} key in the transient menu. @*

The user option @code{anki-noter-anki-format} specifies the value for the @code{ANKI_FORMAT} property on generated cards.  The default is @code{nil}, which means cards use org-mode format.  Set this to a string if your @samp{anki-editor} setup requires a specific format value. @*

@node Template configuration
@section Template configuration

@vindex anki-noter-default-template
@vindex anki-noter-prompt-templates

The user option @code{anki-noter-default-template} specifies which prompt template to use by default.  Its value must be a string matching a key in @code{anki-noter-prompt-templates}.  The default is @samp{"general"}.  Change this if you most often generate cards for a specific domain---for instance, set it to @samp{"programming"} if you primarily read technical material.  You can also change the template per invocation via the @samp{T} key in the transient menu (@ref{The transient menu}). @*

The user option @code{anki-noter-prompt-templates} is an association list of named prompt templates.  Each entry is a cons cell of @code{(NAME . PROMPT-STRING)}, where @code{NAME} is a string used to identify the template and @code{PROMPT-STRING} is the domain-specific instruction appended to the base system prompt.  Three templates are provided by default: @*

@itemize
@item
@samp{"general"} --- for non-fiction material: key facts, definitions, relationships, cause-effect pairs, and notable claims. @*
@item
@samp{"language"} --- for language learning: vocabulary, idiomatic expressions, grammar rules, and bilingual cards when the output language differs from the source. @*
@item
@samp{"programming"} --- for programming and computer science: concepts, API facts, code behavior, algorithm properties, and design patterns, with an emphasis on understanding over recall. @*
@end itemize

To add a custom template, push a new cons cell onto this list: @*

@lisp
(add-to-list 'anki-noter-prompt-templates
             '("philosophy" . "You are generating flashcards about philosophy. Focus on arguments, distinctions, thought experiments, and key claims by specific thinkers."))
@end lisp

@node Citation
@section Citation

@vindex anki-noter-cite-sources
@vindex anki-noter-cite-format

The user option @code{anki-noter-cite-sources} controls whether a source citation is appended to the back of each generated card.  When @code{nil} (the default), no citation is added.  Set this to @code{t} to enable citations.  This default can be toggled per invocation via the @samp{s} key in the transient menu (@ref{The transient menu}). @*

The user option @code{anki-noter-cite-format} controls the format string used for source citations.  The @samp{%s} placeholder is replaced with the source description (file name, URL, or buffer name).  The default is @samp{"Source: %s"}.  Customize this if you prefer a different citation style---for example, @samp{"Ref: %s"} or @samp{"[%s]"}. @*

@node AI model
@section AI model

@vindex anki-noter-backend
@vindex anki-noter-model

The user option @code{anki-noter-backend} specifies the @samp{gptel} backend name for card generation, e.g. @samp{"Gemini"} or @samp{"Claude"}.  When @code{nil} (the default), the backend is inferred from @code{anki-noter-model} if set, otherwise it falls back to @code{gptel-backend}.  Set this when you want to use a specific provider regardless of your global @samp{gptel} default. @*

The user option @code{anki-noter-model} specifies the @samp{gptel} model for card generation, e.g. @code{claude-sonnet-4-5-20250514}.  When @code{nil} (the default), it uses @code{gptel-model}.  If you set a model but not a backend, the backend is inferred automatically by searching the registered @samp{gptel} backends for one that provides the requested model. @*

Both options can be changed per session via the @samp{-m} key in the transient menu (@ref{The transient menu}), which sets @code{anki-noter-model} for the duration of the Emacs session. @*

@node PDF handling
@section PDF handling

@vindex anki-noter-pdf-fallback-command

The user option @code{anki-noter-pdf-fallback-command} specifies the shell command used to extract text from PDF files when the current @samp{gptel} backend does not support native PDF input.  The @samp{%s} placeholder is replaced with the (shell-quoted) file path.  The default is @samp{"pdftotext %s -"}, which sends the extracted text to standard output. @*

Native PDF support is detected automatically: Anthropic (Claude) and Google (Gemini) backends can process PDF files directly via @code{gptel-context-add-file}, so this fallback is only used with other backends such as OpenAI@.  If @samp{pdftotext} is not available on your system, install it (it is part of the @samp{poppler-utils} package on most systems) or configure this option to use an alternative tool. @*

@node Anki integration
@section Anki integration

@vindex anki-noter-auto-push

The user option @code{anki-noter-auto-push} controls whether newly generated notes are pushed to Anki automatically.  When @code{nil} (the default), the package prompts you with a confirmation after inserting cards.  Set this to @code{t} to skip the prompt and push immediately---convenient when you trust the LLM output and want a streamlined workflow.  Pushing requires @samp{anki-editor} and a running AnkiConnect instance. @*

