@node The transient menu
@section The transient menu

@findex anki-noter

The command @code{anki-noter} is the single entry point to the package.  It opens a transient menu that displays all configurable parameters, organized into three groups: source, target, and options.  You configure the parameters you need and then press @samp{g} to generate cards. @*

The transient initializes its values from the corresponding user options and org context: @code{anki-noter-default-template}, @code{anki-noter-card-count}, @code{anki-noter-language}, and @code{anki-noter-cite-sources} supply the defaults for their respective fields, while @code{ANKI_DECK} and @code{ANKI_TAGS} are inherited from the org heading tree when available. @*

The menu is organized as follows: @*

@menu
* Source::
* Target::
* Options::
* Actions::
@end menu

@node Source
@subsection Source

@itemize
@item
@samp{f} (@strong{File}) --- set the source file.  Prompts with @code{read-file-name}.  PDF files are handled transparently: on backends with native PDF support (Anthropic, Google), the file is added to the @samp{gptel} context directly; on other backends, text is extracted via the fallback command (@ref{PDF handling}). @*
@item
@samp{u} (@strong{URL}) --- set a URL as the source.  The page is fetched asynchronously, its HTML is rendered to plain text via @code{shr-render-region}, and the resulting text is sent to the LLM@. @*
@item
@samp{r} (@strong{Page range}) --- set a page range for PDF files (e.g., @samp{"1-20"}).  Only meaningful when a PDF file is set as the source. @*
@end itemize

If neither a file nor a URL is set, the current buffer content is used as the source.  If a region is active, only the selected text is sent. @*

@node Target
@subsection Target

@itemize
@item
@samp{d} (@strong{Deck}) --- set the Anki deck.  Prompts with @code{completing-read} from deck names obtained via @code{anki-editor-deck-names}.  If not set in the transient, the deck is inherited from the org context (@code{ANKI_DECK} property up the heading tree); if no org context value is found, you are prompted interactively when generating. @*
@item
@samp{t} (@strong{Tags}) --- set Anki tags.  Prompts with @code{completing-read-multiple} from tags obtained via @code{anki-editor-all-tags}.  Follows the same fallback logic as deck: org context inheritance, then interactive prompt. @*
@end itemize

@node Options
@subsection Options

@itemize
@item
@samp{T} (@strong{Template}) --- select the prompt template.  Prompts with @code{completing-read} from the keys of @code{anki-noter-prompt-templates}.  Defaults to @code{anki-noter-default-template}. @*
@item
@samp{c} (@strong{Card count}) --- set the target number of cards.  When unset, the LLM decides the appropriate number.  Defaults to @code{anki-noter-card-count}. @*
@item
@samp{l} (@strong{Language}) --- set the output language.  When unset, cards are generated in the same language as the source.  Defaults to @code{anki-noter-language}. @*
@item
@samp{o} (@strong{Topic focus}) --- narrow generation to a specific topic within the source material.  When unset, the LLM considers the full content. @*
@item
@samp{s} (@strong{Cite sources}) --- toggle whether to append a source citation to each card back.  Defaults to @code{anki-noter-cite-sources}. @*
@item
@samp{-m} (@strong{AI model}) --- set the @samp{gptel} model for this session.  Displays the current value of @code{anki-noter-model}; when unset, the global @code{gptel-model} is used.  See @ref{AI model}. @*
@end itemize

@node Actions
@subsection Actions

@itemize
@item
@samp{g} (@strong{Generate}) --- run @code{anki-noter-generate} with the current transient settings. @*
@end itemize

@node Generating cards
@section Generating cards

@findex anki-noter-generate

The command @code{anki-noter-generate} is a suffix action within the @code{anki-noter} transient.  It reads the current transient arguments, determines the insertion point and heading level from the org context, builds a system prompt from the active template and options, sends the source material to the LLM via @samp{gptel}, parses the response, and inserts the resulting org headings at point.  After insertion, it optionally pushes the new notes to Anki (@ref{Anki integration}). @*

The command also performs @emph{incremental generation}: it scans sibling headings that already have an @code{ANKI_NOTE_TYPE} property and includes their front text in the prompt, instructing the LLM not to produce duplicate cards.  This means you can invoke generation multiple times on the same source and get fresh cards each time. @*

The source is determined by the transient arguments: @*

@enumerate
@item
If a @strong{file} is set, that file is used.  PDF files are handled transparently depending on the backend (@ref{PDF handling}). @*
@item
If a @strong{URL} is set, the page is fetched and its rendered text is used. @*
@item
If neither is set, the @strong{current buffer content} (or active region) is used. @*
@end enumerate

The @strong{deck} and @strong{tags} are resolved in order: transient value, then org context inheritance (@code{ANKI_DECK} / @code{ANKI_TAGS} properties up the heading tree), then interactive prompt. @*

While @code{anki-noter-generate} can be called directly with @samp{M-x anki-noter-generate}, it is designed to be invoked from within the transient menu, where its arguments are set via the infix controls described above. @*

